        <h1 style="text-align: center; color: rgb(19, 19, 126);">
            MAJOR SANDEEP UNNIKRISHNAN
        </h1>

        <img style="display: block; margin: auto;"
        src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/7/7d/Major_Sandeep_Unnikrishnan.jpg"
        alt="Major Sandeep Unnikrishnan"
        width="400" height="400">

        <p style="text-align: center; color: black;">
            "Do not come up, I will handle them."  
            These words were not just a command, they were a symbol of unmatched courage.  
            You stood between terror and innocent lives without hesitation.  
            Your bravery reminds every Indian what true sacrifice looks like.  
            Because of heroes like you, we sleep peacefully every night.  
            Your legacy is not just remembered, it is lived in every heartbeat of this nation.
        </p>

        <h3 style="text-align: center; color:rgb(148, 6, 6);">
            INTRODUCTION
        </h3>

        <p style="text-align: center; color: black;">
            Major Sandeep Unnikrishnan (15 March 1977 – 28 November 2008) 
            was an officer in the Indian Army serving in the National Security Guard (NSG). 
            He was martyred during the 2008 Mumbai attacks while rescuing hostages at the Taj Hotel. 
            He was awarded the Ashoka Chakra, India's highest peacetime gallantry award, 
            for his extraordinary bravery and leadership.
        </p>

        <h3 style="text-align: center; color:rgb(148, 6, 6);">
            BIRTH AND FAMILY
        </h3>

        <p style="text-align: center; color: black;">
            He was born on 15 March 1977 in Kozhikode, Kerala, and raised in Bengaluru. 
            His father, K. Unnikrishnan, was a retired ISRO officer, and his mother, Dhanalakshmi, 
            was a homemaker. From a young age, he showed discipline, leadership, and a strong sense of duty. 
            He completed his schooling in Bengaluru and later joined the National Defence Academy (NDA), 
            where his journey as a soldier truly began.
        </p>

